DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a light shown throughout the 24 hours without change of character. IHO Chart Specifications, M-4

DataDictionaryReference.Name: daytime light
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a light which is only exhibited by day.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: fog light
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a light which is exhibited in fog or conditions of reduced visibility.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: night light
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a light which is only exhibited at night.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Exposition of sounding
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Indicates objects with a 'value of sounding' not within the range of depth of the surrounding depth area.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: This attribute indicates objects with a ‘value of sounding’ not within the range of depth of the surrounding depth area. These objects could be a potential danger for navigation.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: within the range of depth of the surrounding depth area
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth corresponds to the depth range of the surrounding depth area. i.e. the depth is not shoaler than the minimum depth of the surrounding depth area or deeper than the maximum depth of the surrounding depth area.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: shoaler than the range of depth of the surrounding depth area
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth is shoaler than the minimum depth of the surrounding depth area.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: deeper than the range of depth of the surrounding depth area
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth is deeper than the maximum depth of the surrounding depth area.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: harbour-master's office
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the office of the local official who has charge of mooring and berthing of vessels, collecting harbour fees, etc. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2191)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: custom office
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an office which is charged with enforcing customs regulations.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: health office
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the office which is charged with the administration of health laws and sanitary inspections. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: hospital
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an institution or establishment providing medical or surgical treatment for the ill or wounded. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: post office
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the public department, agency or organisation responsible primarily for the collection, transmission and distribution of mail. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: hotel
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an establishment, especially of a comfortable or luxurious kind, where paying visitors are provided with accommodation, meals and other services. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: railway station
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a building with platforms where trains arrive, load, discharge and depart. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: police station
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the office of the local police force.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: water-police station
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the headquarters of a local water-police force.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: pilot office
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the office or headquarters of pilots; the place where the services of a pilot may be obtained. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3845)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: pilot lookout
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a distinctive structure on shore from which personnel keep watch upon events at sea or along the coast. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2917)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: bank office
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an office for custody, deposit, loan, exchange or issue of money. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: headquarters for district control
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the quarters of an executive officer (director, manager, etc.) with responsibility for an administrative area.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: transit shed/warehouse
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a building or part of a building for storage of wares or goods. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: factory
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a building or buildings with equipment for manufacturing; a workshop. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: power station
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a stationary plant containing apparatus for large scale conversion of some form of energy (such as hydraulic, steam, chemical or nuclear energy) into electrical energy. (McGraw-Hill Dictionary of Scientific and Technical Terms, 3rd Edition, 1984)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: administrative
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a building for the management of affairs. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: educational facility
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a building concerned with education (eg. school, college, university, etc.)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: church
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a building for public Christian worship. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: chapel
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a place for Christian worship other than a parish, cathedral or church, especially one attached to a private house or institution. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: temple
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a building for public Jewish worship. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: pagoda
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a Hindu or Buddhist temple or sacred building. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: shinto shrine
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a building for public Shinto worship. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: buddhist temple
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: see pagoda.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: mosque
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a Muslim place of worship. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: marabout
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a shrine marking the burial place of a Muslim holy man. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: lookout
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: keeping a watch upon events at sea or along the coast. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32,5th Edition,2917)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: communication
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: transmitting and/or receiving electronic communication signals. (adapted from Digital Geographic Information Standard - DIGEST)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: television
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: broadcast of television signals.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: radio
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: broadcast of radio signals.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: radar
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a method, system or technique of using beamed, reflected, and timed radio waves for detecting, locating, or tracking objects, and for measuring altitudes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition,4158)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: light support
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: supporting a light

DataDictionaryReference.Name: microwave
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: broadcasting and receiving signals using microwaves.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: cooling
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: dissipating heat.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: observation
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a place from which the surroundings can be observed but at which a watch is not habitually maintained. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition,2917)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: time ball
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a visual time signal in form of a ball

DataDictionaryReference.Name: clock
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: visual time signal. (adapted from S-32, 5th Edition, 5536)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: control
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: used to control the flow of air, rail, or marine traffic. (Digital Geographic Information Standard - DIGEST)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: airship mooring
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a facility to secure an airship. (adapted from Digital Geographic Information Standard - DIGEST)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: stadium
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a large usually unroofed building with tiers of seats for spectators

DataDictionaryReference.Name: bus station
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a location at which buses arrive and from which they depart.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Height
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The value of the vertical distance to the highest point of the object, measured from a specified vertical datum.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: Height must not be used for floating objects. The unit of measure is defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 ft.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Horizontal Accuracy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The best estimate of the horizontal accuracy of horizontal clearance and distances.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Horizontal clearance
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The width of an object, such as a canal or a tunnel, which is available for safe navigation. This may, or may not, be the same as the total physical width of the object.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The unit of measure is defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 ft.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Horizontal length
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: A measurement of the longer of two linear axis. (Digital Geographic Information Working Group -DGIWG, Oct.87)
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The unit of measure is defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 ft.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Horizontal width
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: A measurement of the shorter of two linear axis. (Digital Geographic Information Working Group -DGIWG, Oct.87)
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The unit of measure is defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 ft.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Information
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Textual information about the object.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The textual information could be, for example, a list, a table or a text. This attribute should be used, for example, to hold the information that is shown on paper charts by cautionary and explanatory notes. No formatting of text is possible within INFORM. If formatted text is required, then the attribute TXTDSC must be used.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Information in national language
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Textual information in national language characters
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The attribute 'information in national language' encodes any textual information about an object using a specified national language. The textual information could be, for example, a list, a table or a text. This attribute should be used, for example, to hold the information that is shown on paper charts by cautionary and explanatory notes.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Jurisdiction
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The jurisdiction applicable to an administrative area

DataDictionaryReference.Name: international
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: involving more than one country; covering more than one national area.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: national
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area administered or controlled by a single nation.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: national sub-division
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area smaller than the nation in which it lies.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Light characteristic
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: A selection of the above characteristics is defined and illustrated diagrammatically in IHO Chart Specifications, M-4, 471.2.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: fixed
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a signal light that shows continuously, in any given direction, with constant luminous intensity and colour. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2780)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: flashing
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a rhythmic light in which the total duration of light in a period is clearly shorter than the total duration of darkness and all the appearances of light are of equal duration. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2783)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: long-flashing
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a flashing light in which a single flash of not less than two seconds duration is regularly repeated. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2796)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: quick-flashing
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a light exhibiting without interruption very rapid regular alternations of light and darkness. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2803)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: very quick-flashing
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a flashing light in which flashes are repeated at a rate of not less than 80 flashes per minute but less than 160 flashes per minute

DataDictionaryReference.Name: ultra quick flashing
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a flashing light in which flashes are repeated at a rate of not less than 160 flashes per minute

DataDictionaryReference.Name: isophased
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a light with all durations of light and darkness equal. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2779)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: occulting
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a rhythmic light in which the total duration of light in a period is clearly longer than the total duration of darkness and all the eclipses are of equal duration

DataDictionaryReference.Name: interrupted quick-flashing
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a quick light in which the sequence of flashes is interrupted by regularly repeated eclipses of constant and long duration. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2790)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: interrupted very quick-flashing
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a light in which the very rapid alterations of light and darkness are interrupted at regular intervals by eclipses of long duration

DataDictionaryReference.Name: interrupted ultra quick-flashing
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a light in which the ultra quick flashes (160 or more per minute) are interrupted at regular intervals by eclipses of long duration

DataDictionaryReference.Name: morse
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a rhythmic light in which appearances of light of two clearly different durations are grouped to represent a character or characters in the Morse code

DataDictionaryReference.Name: alternating
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a signal light that shows, in any given direction, two or more colours in a regularly repeated sequence with a regular periodicity

DataDictionaryReference.Name: faint
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a decrease in the apparent intensity of a light which may occur in the case of partial obstructions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: intensified
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a light in a sector is intensified (i.e. has longer range than other sectors). (Bundesamt für Seeschiffahrt und Hydrographie, Germany)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: obscured
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: said of the arc of a light sector designated by its limiting bearings in which the light is not visible from seaward. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3492)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: partially obscured
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: this value specifies that parts of the sector are obscured.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: IALA A
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: navigational aids conform to the International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA A system.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: IALA B
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: navigational aids conform to the International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA B system.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Multiplicity of lights
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The number of lights of identical character that exist as a co-located group.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Nationality
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The nationality of the specific object.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: Indication: the nationality is encoded by a 2 character- code following ISO 3166 (refer to Annex A to S-57 Appendix A);

DataDictionaryReference.Name: mud
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: soft, wet earth

DataDictionaryReference.Name: clay
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: (particles of less than 0.002 mm); stiff, sticky earth that becomes hard when baked.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: silt
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: (particles of 0.002-0.0625 mm); when dried on hand will rub off easily.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: sand
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: (particles of 0.0625-2.0 mm); tiny grains of crushed or worn rock.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: stone
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a general term for rock fragments ranging in size from pebbles and gravel to boulders or a large rock mass. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 5059)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: gravel
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: (particles of 2.0-4.0 mm); small stones with coarse sand.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: pebbles
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: (particles of 4.0-64.0 mm); small stones made smooth and round by being rolled in water.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: cobbles
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: (particles of 64.0-256.0 mm); stones worn round and smooth by water and used for paving.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: rock
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: any formation of natural origin that constitutes an integral part of the lithosphere. The natural occurring material that forms firm, hard, and solid masses. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4415)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: lava
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the fluid or semi-fluid matter flowing from a volcano. The substance that results from the cooling of the molten rock. Part of the ocean bed is composed of lava. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2680)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: coral
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: hard calcareous skeletons of many tribes of marine polyps. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 1061)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: shells
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: exoskeletons of various water dwelling animals. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4680)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: boulder
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a rounded rock with diameter of 256 mm or larger. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 527)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: masonry
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: constructed of brick or stone.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: concreted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: constructed of concrete, a material made of sand and gravel that is united by cement into a hardened mass used for roads, foundations, etc. (adapted from the Illustrated Contemporary Dictionary, Encyclopaedic Edition, 1978)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: loose boulders
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: constructed from large stones or blocks of concrete, often placed loosely for protection against waves or water turbulence.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: hard surfaced
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: constructed with a surface of hard material, usually a term applied to roads surfaced with asphalt or concrete.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: unsurfaced
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: constructed with no extra protection, usually a term applied to roads not surfaced with a hard material.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: wooden
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: constructed from wood.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: metal
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: constructed from metal.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: glass reinforced plastic (GRP)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: constructed from a plastic material strengthened with fibres of glass.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: painted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the application of paint to some other construction or natural feature.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Nature of surface - qualifying terms
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Nature of surface - qualifying terms

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Fine
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: falls within the smallest size continuum for a particular nature of surface term

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Medium
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: falls within the moderate size continuum for a particular nature of surface term

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Coarse
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: falls within the largest size continuum for a particular nature of surface term

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Broken
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: fractured or in pieces

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Object class definition
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Specifies the defining characteristics of a ‘new object’.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Object class name
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Specifies the descriptive name of a ‘new object’ feature object class.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Object name
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The individual name of an object.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Object name in national language
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Name of object in national language characters
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The attribute 'object name in national language' encodes the individual name of an object in the specified national language.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Orientation
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The angular distance measured from true north to the major axis of the object. (Digital Geographic Information Working Group -DGIWG, Oct.87)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Periodic date end
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The end of the active period for a seasonal object (e.g. a buoy).
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: See also 'date end' (DATEND).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Periodic date start
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The start of the active period for a seasonal object (e.g. a buoy).
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: See also 'date start' (DATSTA).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Pictorial representation
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Indicates whether a pictorial representation of the object is available.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The 'pictorial representation' could be a drawing or a photo. The string encodes the file name of an external graphic file (pixel/vector).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Pilot district
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The area within which a particular pilotage service operates.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Pilot district in national language
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Pilot district (c…): string of national language characters

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Positional Accuracy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The best estimate of the accuracy of a position. The expected input is the maximum of the two-dimensional error. The error is assumed to be positive and negative. The plus/minus character shall not be encoded.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The unit of measure is defined in the PUNI subfield of the DSPM record, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 mm.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Product
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The attribute 'product' encodes the various substances which are transported, stored or exploited.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: oil
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a thick, slippery liquid that will not dissolve in water, usually petroleum based in the context of storage tanks. (adapted from the Oxford Minidictionary, Third Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: gas
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a substance with particles that can move freely, usually a fuel substance in the context of storage tanks. (adapted from the Oxford Minidictionary, Third Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: water
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a colourless, odourless, tasteless liquid that is a compound of hydrogen and oxygen. (adapted from the Oxford Minidictionary, Third Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: stone
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a general term for rock fragments. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 5059)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: coal
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a hard black mineral that is burned as fuel. (adapted from the Oxford Minidictionary, Third Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: ore
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a solid rock or mineral from which metal is obtained. (adapted form the Oxford Minidictionary, Third Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: chemicals
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: any substance obtained by or used in a chemical process. (adapted from the Oxford Minidictionary, Third Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: drinking water
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: water that is suitable for human consumption. (adapted from the Oxford Minidictionary, Third Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: sand
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: tiny grains of crushed or worn rock. (adapted from the Oxford Minidictionary, Third Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: timber
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: wood prepared for use in building or carpentry. (adapted from the Oxford Minidictionary, Third Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: scrap metal
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: discarded metal suitable for being reprocessed. (adapted from the Oxford Minidictionary, Third Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: liquified natural gas (LNG)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a compressed gas consisting of flammable light hydrocarbons and derived from natural gas.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: liquified petroleum gas (LPG)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a compressed gas consisting of flammable light hydrocarbons and derived from petroleum. (adapted from Websters Third New)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: cement
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a substance made of powdered lime and clay, mixed with water. (adapted from the Websters New World Dictionary)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: grain
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a small hard seed, especially that of any cereal plant such as wheat, rice, corn, rye etc. (adapted from the Websters New World Dictionary)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: approximate
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a position that is considered to be less than third-order accuracy, but is generally considered to be within 30.5 metres of its correct geographic location. Also may apply to an object whose position does not remain fixed. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 213, 3967, and IHO Specifications, M-4, 424.1)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: precisely known
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a position that is of a known value, such as the position of an anchor berth or other defined object.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Quality of sounding measurement
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The attribute 'quality of sounding measurement' indicates the reliability of the value of sounding.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: depth known
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth from chart datum to the bottom is a known value.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: depth unknown
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth from chart datum to the bottom is unknown.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: doubtful sounding
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a depth that may be less than indicated. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4840)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: unreliable sounding
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a depth that is considered to be an unreliable value.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: least depth known
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the shoalest depth over a feature is of known value. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2705)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: least depth unknown, safe clearance at depth shown
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the least depth over a feature is unknown, but there is considered to be safe clearance at this depth.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: value reported (not surveyed)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: depth value obtained from a report, but not fully surveyed.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: value reported (not confirmed)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: depth value obtained from a report, which it has not been possible to confirm.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: maintained depth
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth at which a channel is kept by human influence, usually by dredging. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3057)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: not regularly maintained
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: depths may be altered by human influence, but will not be routinely maintained.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Radar wave length
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The distance between two successive peaks (or other points of identical phase) on an electromagnetic wave in the radar band of the electromagnetic spectrum.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The attribute 'radar transponder beacon wavelength' encodes the specific wavelength at which a radar transponder beacon transmits. Radar transponder beacons generally work on the following wavelengths: 3cm (X) Band, 10cm (S) Band. Nevertheless, wavelengths outside the marine band are used.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Reference year for magnetic variation
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The reference calendar year for magnetic variation values.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Restriction
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The official legal statute of each kind of restricted area.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: Defines the kind of restriction(s), e.g., the restriction for 'a game preserve' may be 'entry prohibited', the restriction for an 'anchoring prohibition' is 'anchoring prohibited'. A short explanation may be given by the use of the attribute 'INFORM'.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: anchoring prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which anchoring is not permitted.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: anchoring restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which anchoring is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: fishing prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which fishing is not permitted.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: fishing restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which fishing is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: trawling prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which trawling is not permitted.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: trawling restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which trawling is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: entry prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which navigation and/or anchoring is prohibited.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: entry restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which navigation is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: dredging prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which dredging is not permitted.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: dredging restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which dredging is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: diving prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which diving is not permitted.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: diving restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which diving is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: no wake
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: mariners must adjust the speed of their vessels to reduce the wave or wash which may cause erosion or disturb moored vessels.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: area to be avoided
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an IMO designated area to be avoided, defined as a routeing measure.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: construction prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the erection of permanent or temporary fixed structures or artificial islands is prohibited.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: discharging prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which discharging or dumping is prohibited

DataDictionaryReference.Name: discharging restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by an appropriate authority, within which discharging or dumping is restricted in accordance with specified conditions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: industrial or mineral exploration/development prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which industrial or mineral exploration and development are prohibited.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: industrial or mineral exploration/development restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by an appropriate authority, within which industrial or mineral exploration and development is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: drilling prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which excavating a hole on the sea-bottom with a drill is prohibited.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: drilling restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by an appropriate authority, within which excavating a hole on the sea-bottom with a drill is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: removal of historical artifacts prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which the removal of historical artifacts is prohibited.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: cargo transhipment (lightering) prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area in which cargo transhipment (lightering) is prohibited.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: dragging prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area in which the dragging of anything along the bottom, e.g. bottom trawling, is prohibited.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: stopping prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area in which a vessel is prohibited from stopping.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: landing prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area in which landing is prohibited.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: speed restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which speed is restricted.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: use of spuds prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The use of anchoring spuds (telescopic piles) is prohibited

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Scale minimum
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The minimum scale at which the object may be used e.g. for ECDIS presentation.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The modulus of the scale is indicated, that is 1:1 250 000 is encoded as 1250000.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Sector limit one
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. (Advanced Learner=s Dictionary, 2nd Edition) Sector limit 1 specifies the first limit of the sector. The order of sector limit 1 and sector limit 2 is clockwise around the central object (e.g. a light).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Sector limit two
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. (Advanced Learner=s Dictionary, 2nd Edition) The sector limit 2 specifies the second limit of the sector. The order of sector limit 1 and sector limit 2 is clockwise around the central object (e.g. a light).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Signal frequency
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The frequency of a signal.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Signal generation
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The attribute 'signal generation' encodes the mechanism used to generate a fog signal.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: automatically
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: signal generation is initiated by a self regulating mechanism such as a timer or light sensor.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: by wave action
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the signal is generated by the motion of the sea surface such as a bell in a buoy.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Signal group
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The number of signals, the combination of signals or the morse character(s) within one period of full sequence.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Signal period
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The time occupied by an entire cycle of intervals of light and eclipse.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Signal sequence
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The sequence of times occupied by intervals of light and eclipse for all 'light characteristics' except for occulting where the sequence of times is occupied by intervals of eclipse and light.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The 'signal sequence' for all 'light characteristics' except for occulting is indicated using a fixed format to encode the value of intervals of light (L) and eclipse (E).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Sounding accuracy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The best estimate of the accuracy of the sounding data. The maximum of the one-dimensional error. The error is assumed to be positive and negative. The plus/minus character shall not be encoded.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The unit of measure is defined in the DUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the DUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 fm or 0.1 ft.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Source date
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The production date of the source, e.g. the date of measurement.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Source indication
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Information about the source of the object.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: permanent
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: intended to last or function indefinitely

DataDictionaryReference.Name: occasional
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: acting on special occasions; happening irregularly. (The Concise Oxford Dictionary, 7th Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: recommended
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: presented as worthy of confidence, acceptance, use, etc. (The Macquarie Dictionary, 1988)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: not in use
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: no longer used for the purpose intended; disused.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: periodic/intermittent
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: recurring at intervals

DataDictionaryReference.Name: reserved
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: set apart for some specific use.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: temporary
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: meant to last only for a time. (The Concise Oxford Dictionary)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: private
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: not in public ownership or operation.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: mandatory
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: compulsory; enforced. (The Concise Oxford Dictionary, 7th Edition)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: extinguished
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: no longer lit

DataDictionaryReference.Name: illuminated
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: lit by floodlights, strip lights, etc.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: historic
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: famous in history; of historical interest

DataDictionaryReference.Name: public
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: belonging to, available to, used or shared by, the community as a whole and not restricted to private use. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: synchronized
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: occur at a time, coincide in point of time, be contemporary or simultaneous

DataDictionaryReference.Name: watched
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: looked at or observed over a period of time especially so as to be aware of any movement or change. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: un-watched
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: usually automatic in operation, without any permanently-stationed personnel to superintend it. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2814)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: existence doubtful
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an object that has been reported but has not been definitely determined to exist.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Survey authority
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The authority which was responsible for the survey.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The attribute 'survey authority' encodes the name of the source survey authority.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Survey date - end
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The end date of the survey.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Survey date - start
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The start date of the survey.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: controlled survey
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a thorough survey usually conducted with reference to guidelines.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Symbol instruction
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: This specifies the S‐52 Presentation Library symbol instruction to be adopted in ECDIS for the new object class (as specified in the S‐52 Symbol Library ‐ Addendum to S‐52 Presentation Library).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: found by echo-sounder
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth was determined by using an instrument that determines depth of water by measuring the time interval between emission of a sonic or ultrasonic signal and return of its echo from the bottom. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 1547)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: found by side-scan-sonar
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth was computed from a record produced by active sonar in which fixed acoustic beams are directed into the water perpendicularly to the direction of travel to scan the bottom and generate a record of the bottom configuration. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 4710)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: found by multi-beam
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth was determined by using a wide swath echo sounder that uses multiple beams to measure depths directly below and transverse to the ship's track. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 3339)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: found by diver
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth was determined by a person skilled in the practice of diving. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 1422)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: found by lead-line
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth was determined by using a line, graduated with attached marks and fastened to a sounding lead. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 2698)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: swept by wire-drag
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the given area was determined to be free from navigational dangers to a certain depth by towing a buoyed wire at the desired depth by two launches, or a least depth was identified using the same technique. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5248, 6013)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: found by laser
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth was determined by using an instrument that measures distance by emitting timed pulses of laser light and measuring the time between emission and reception of the reflected pulses. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 2763)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: swept by vertical acoustic system
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the given area has been swept using a system comprised of multiple echo sounder transducers attached to booms deployed from the survey vessel.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: found by electromagnetic sensor
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth was determined by using an instrument that compares electromagnetic signals. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 1571)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: photogrammetry
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth was determined by applying mathematical techniques to photographs. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 3791)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: satellite imagery
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth was determined by using instruments placed aboard an artificial satellite. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 4509)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: found by levelling
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the depth was determined by using levelling techniques to find the elevation of the point relative to a datum. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 2741)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: swept by side-scan-sonar
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the given area was determined to be free from navigational dangers to a certain depth by towing a side-scan-sonar. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5248, 4710) [415.2]

DataDictionaryReference.Name: computer generated
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the sounding was determined from a bottom model constructed using a computer.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Textual description
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The string encodes the file name of an external text file that contains the text in English
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The attribute 'textual description' indicates that a file containing text extracted from relevant pilot books or navigational publications is available.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Textual description in national language
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The file name of an external text file that contains the text in a national language.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The attribute 'textual description in national language' indicates whether a text file containing text extracted from relevant pilot books or navigational publications is available.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Topmark/daymark shape
DataDictionaryReference.Reference: 463.1 (for International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA systems only)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: cone, point up
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: is where the vertex points up.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: cone, point down
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: is where the vertex points down.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: sphere
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a body the surface of which is at all points equidistant from the centre. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2). Spheres are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmarks (safe water).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: 2 spheres
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: two black spheres are commonly used as an International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmark (isolated danger).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: cylinder (can)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a solid geometrical figure generated by straight lines fixed in direction and describing with one of point a closed curve, especially a circle (in which case the figure is circular cylinder, it's ends being parallel circles). (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2). Cylinders are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmarks (lateral).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: board
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: usually of rectangular shape, made from timber or metal and used to provide a contrast with the natural background of a daymark. The actual daymark is often painted on to this board.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: x-shape (St. Andrew's cross)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: having a shape or a cross-section like the capital letter X. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2). An x-shape as an International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmark should be 3 dimensional in shape. It is made of at least three crossed bars.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: upright cross (St George's cross)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a cross with one vertical member and one horizontal member, i.e. similar in shape to the character '+'.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: cube, point up
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a cube standing on one of its vertexes.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: 2 cones, point to point
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their vertices together in the centre.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: 2 cones, base to base
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their bases together in the centre and their vertices pointing up and down.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: rhombus (diamond)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a plane figure having four equal sides and equal opposite angles (two acute and two obtuse); an oblique equilateral parallelogram. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: 2 cones (points upward)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their their vertices pointing up

DataDictionaryReference.Name: 2 cones (points downward)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their their vertices pointing down

DataDictionaryReference.Name: besom, point up (broom or perch)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a bundle of rods or twigs. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 1)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: besom, point down (broom or perch)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a bundle of rods or twigs. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 1)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: flag
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a flag mounted on a short pole.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: sphere over rhombus
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: A sphere located above a rhombus.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: square
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a plane figure with four right angles and four equal straight sides (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: rectangle, horizontal
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a plane figure with four right angles and four straight sides, opposite sides being parallel and equal in length where the two longer opposite sides are standing horizontally (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: rectangle, vertical
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a plane figure with four right angles and four straight sides, opposite sides being parallel and equal in length where the two longer opposite sides are standing vertically (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: trapezium, up
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a quadrilateral having one pair of opposite sides parallel which stands on its longer parallel side. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: trapezium, down
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a quadrilateral having one pair of opposite sides parallel which stands on its shorter parallel side. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: triangle, point up
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a figure having three angles and three sides with point up. (New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: triangle, point down
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a figure having three angles and three sides with point down. (New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: circle
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a perfectly round plane figure whose circumference is everywhere equidistant from its centre. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 1)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: two upright crosses (one over the other)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: two upright crosses, generally vertically disposed one above the other.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: T-shape
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: having a shape like the capital letter T.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: triangle pointing up over a circle
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a triangle, vertex uppermost, located above a circle.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: upright cross over a circle
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an upright cross located above a circle.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: rhombus over a circle
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a rhombus located above a circle.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: circle over a triangle pointing up
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a circle located over a triangle, vertex uppermost.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: inbound
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: traffic flow in a general direction toward a port or similar destination.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: outbound
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: traffic flow in a general direction away from a port or similar point of origin.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: one-way
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: traffic flow in one general direction only.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: two-way
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: traffic flow in two generally opposite directions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Value of annual change in magnetic variation
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The annual change in magnetic variation values.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Value of depth contour
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The depth of a sea bottom contour.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: Drying contours are indicated by a negative value. The unit of measure is defined in the DUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the DUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 fm or 0.1 ft.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Value of magnetic variation
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The magnetic variation value.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Value of maximum range
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The extreme distance at which an object can be seen or a signal detected.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: This attribute does not apply to lights where the attribute 'value of nominal range' should be used.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Value of nominal range
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The nominal range at which an object can be seen or a signal detected

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Value of sounding
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The value of the measurement of a sounding relative to the chart datum.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: A drying height is indicated by a negative value. The unit of measure is defined in the DUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the DUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 fm or 0.1 ft.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Vertical Accuracy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The one-dimensional error. The error is assumed to be positive and negative. The plus/minus character shall not be encoded.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Vertical clearance
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The vertical clearance measured from the plane towards the object overhead.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: In the case of cables carrying high voltages an additional clearance of from 2 to 5 metres may be needed to avoid an electrical discharge. When known, the authorized safe clearance (known in the UK as the Safe Overhead Clearance) which is the physical clearance minus a safety margin shall be stated (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). See also 'vertical clearance safe'. The unit of measure is defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 ft.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Vertical clearance, closed
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The vertical clearance of an object in closed condition (e.g. a closed lifting bridge) measured from the plane towards the object overhead.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The unit of measure is defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 ft.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Vertical clearance, open
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The vertical clearance of an object in opened condition (e.g. an opened lifting bridge) measured from the plane towards the object overhead.
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The unit of measure is defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 ft.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Vertical datum
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Vertical datum

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Lowest low water
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an arbitrary level conforming to the lowest tide observed at a place, or some what lower.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Lowest astronomical tide
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: (LAT) - the lowest tide level which can be predicted to occur under average meterological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2936)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Local datum
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an arbitrary datum defined by a local harbour authority, from which levels and tidal heights are measured by this authority.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Highest astronomical tide
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: (HAT) - the highest tidal level which can be predicted to occur under average meteorological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2244).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Vertical length
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Vertical length

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Water level effect
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The attribute 'water level effect' encodes the effect of the surrounding water on an object.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: partly submerged at high water
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: partially covered and partially dry at high water.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: always dry
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: not covered at high water under average meteorological conditions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: always under water/submerged
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: remains covered by water at all times under average meteorological conditions.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: covers and uncovers
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: expression intended to indicate an area of a reef or other projection from the bottom of a body of water which periodically extends above and is submerged below the surface. Also referred to as dries or uncovers. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 1111)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: awash
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: flush with, or washed by the waves at low water under average meteorological conditions. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 308)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: floating
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: resting or moving on the surface of a liquid without sinking (Concise Oxford Dictionary)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Additional mark
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Shape and position of an additional board on a notice mark
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The kind and location of an additional mark at a notice mark

DataDictionaryReference.Name: top (board)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a rectangular board at the top of the main sign

DataDictionaryReference.Name: bottom (board)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a rectangular board at the bottom of the main sign

DataDictionaryReference.Name: right (triangle to the right)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a triangular board at the right side of the main sign

DataDictionaryReference.Name: left (triangle to the left)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a triangular board at the left side of the main sign

DataDictionaryReference.Name: bottom (triangle to the bottom)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a triangular board at the bottom of the main sign

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Allowed consumption
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The maximum allowed power that may be used by the vessel

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Amount of amperage
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The maximum electric amperage possible

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Assemblies of ship (excluding)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Excluding list of assemblies of ships for the applicability of a feature

DataDictionaryReference.Name: convoy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a rigid or towed convoy of craft

DataDictionaryReference.Name: formation
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the manner in which a convoy is assembled

DataDictionaryReference.Name: rigid convoy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a pushed convoy or breasted up formation

DataDictionaryReference.Name: pushed convoy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a rigid assembly of craft of which at least one is positioned in front of the craft providing the power for propelling the convoy, known as the "pusher(s)"; a convoy composed of a pusher craft and a pushed craft coupled so as to permit guided articulation is also considered as rigid

DataDictionaryReference.Name: breasted up formation
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an assembly of craft coupled rigidly side by side, none of which is positioned in front of the craft propelling the assembly

DataDictionaryReference.Name: towed convoy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an assembly of one or more craft, floating establishments or floating installations towed by one or more self-propelled craft forming part of the convoy

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Assemblies of ship (including)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Including list of assemblies of ships for the applicability of a feature

DataDictionaryReference.Name: convoy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a rigid or towed convoy of craft

DataDictionaryReference.Name: formation
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: the manner in which a convoy is assembled

DataDictionaryReference.Name: rigid convoy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a pushed convoy or breasted up formation

DataDictionaryReference.Name: pushed convoy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a rigid assembly of craft of which at least one is positioned in front of the craft providing the power for propelling the convoy, known as the "pusher(s)"; a convoy composed of a pusher craft and a pushed craft coupled so as to permit guided articulation is also considered as rigid

DataDictionaryReference.Name: breasted up formation
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an assembly of craft coupled rigidly side by side, none of which is positioned in front of the craft propelling the assembly

DataDictionaryReference.Name: towed convoy
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an assembly of one or more craft, floating establishments or floating installations towed by one or more self-propelled craft forming part of the convoy

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Average Passing Time Reference
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The string encodes the file name of an external file

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Bank of the waterway
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Bank of the river (waterway)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: left
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: left bank of the river

DataDictionaryReference.Name: right
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: right bank of the river

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Bunker vessel, availability
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Indication of the availability of a bunker vessel

DataDictionaryReference.Name: bunker vessel available
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a bunker vessel is available

DataDictionaryReference.Name: no bunker vessel available
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a bunker vessel is not available

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Adriatic level
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The average height of the surface of the Adriatic sea at the tide station of Trieste in Italy.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Amsterdam Ordnance Datum (NAP)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Dutch gravitational reference level that is approximately the average summer height of the North Sea.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Mean Sea Level
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: (MSL) - the average height of the surface of the sea at a tide station for all stages of the tide over a 19-year period, usually determined from hourly height readings measured from a fixed predetermined reference level. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3156)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: National Geodetic Vertical Datum - NGVD29
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The name, after May 10, 1973, of the Sea Level Datum of 1929.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: North American Vertical Datum - NAVD88
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The vertical control datum established in 1991 by the minimum-constraint adjustment of geodetic leveling observations in Canada, the United States, and Mexico.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Mean sea level 1912

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Mean sea level 1929
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: A vertical control datum established for vertical control in the United States by the general adjustment of 1929.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: berthing restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which berthing is restricted

DataDictionaryReference.Name: making fast prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which vessels, assemblies of floating material or floating establishments may not make fast to the bank.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: making fast restricted
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which making fast to the bank is restricted

DataDictionaryReference.Name: turning prohibited
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which all turning is generally prohibited

DataDictionaryReference.Name: restricted fairway depth
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which the fairway depth is restricted.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: restricted fairway width
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an area within which the fairway width is restricted.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: use of spuds prohibited

DataDictionaryReference.Name: NOx emission restricted

DataDictionaryReference.Name: speed through water

DataDictionaryReference.Name: fishing vessel
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a vessel that is used and equipped for the fishing of living aquatic resources.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: special purpose vessel.
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a vessel that fulfills special purposes e.g. hovercrafts, pilot boats

DataDictionaryReference.Name: man of War

DataDictionaryReference.Name: submarine
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a vessel that is capable of operating for an extended period of time underwater.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: bulk carrier

DataDictionaryReference.Name: seaplane

DataDictionaryReference.Name: tugboat
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a powerful small boat designed to pull or push larger ships or powerless barges.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: passenger vessel
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a vessel which is designed for carrying passengers and which serves mainly as cruise vessel.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: ferry
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: a vessel which is designed for carrying passengers, and sometimes their vehicles, on scheduled services.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: UN location code
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The attribute unlocd should be used to encode the UN Location Code (http://www.unece.org/cefact/locode/service/main.htm) or - in Europe - the Inland Ship Reporting Standard (ISRS) Code
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: The ISRS Code exists of: - UN country code (2 digits), - UN Location code (3 digits, “XXX” if not available), - Fairway section number (5 numerical digits, to be determined by the national authority; a side branch should have an own section number, when there are special restrictions, e.g. bridges), - terminal code or passage point code (5 alphanumerical digits, “00000”if not available), - fairway section hectometre (5 numerical digits, hectometre at the center of the area, “00000”if not available). If the ISRS code is not available, the code of the Nordersoft RIS-Index may be used

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Lowest astronomical tide
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: (LAT) - the lowest tide level which can be predicted to occur under average meterological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2936)

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Local datum
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: an arbitrary datum defined by a local harbour authority, from which leves and tidal heights are measured by this authority.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Highest astronomical tide
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: (HAT) - the highest tidal level which can be predicted to occur under average meteorological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2244).

DataDictionaryReference.Definition: low water reference level of the local area

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Local high water reference level
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: high water reference level of the local area

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Local mean water reference level
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: mean water reference level of the local area

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Equivalent height of water (German GlW)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: A low water level which is the result of a defined low water discharge - called "equivalent discharge".
DataDictionaryReference.Remark: A new agreement upon the value of the "equivalent discharge" is made every 10 years by the "Central Commission for Navigation on the Rhine". On average the "equivalent height of water" is currently fallen short of only at about 10 days per year [2002]

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Highest Shipping Height of Water (German HSW)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: upper limit of water levels where navigation is allowed

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Reference low water level according to Danube Commission
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The water level at a discharge, which is exceeded 94 % of the year within a period of 30 years.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Highest shipping height of water according to Danube Commission
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The water level at a discharge, which is exceeded 1 % of the year within a period of 30 years.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Dutch river low water reference level (OLR)
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: The water level at a discharge, which is exceeded 95 % of the year within a period of 20 years.

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Russian project water level
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Conditional low water level with established probability (Hydrographic Terminology Dictionary, HDNO, 1984).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Russian normal backwater level
DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Highest water level derived from the upper backwater stream in watercourse or reservoir under the normal operational conditions. (Hydrographic Terminology Dictionary, HDNO, 1984).

DataDictionaryReference.Name: Dutch estuary low water reference level (OLW)
Vertical river datum reference level value

DataDictionaryReference.Definition: Units of measure for water displacement
